The '''white-tailed jay''' ('''''Cyanocorax mystacalis'''''), also known as the moustached jay, is a species of [[bird]] in the crow family [[Corvidae]]. It is found in [[Ecuador]] and [[Peru]]. It has a black face with white spots above and below the eyes, and a small white moustachial stripe. It has a white [[List of terms used in bird topography|nape]], belly, and underparts. Its back and wings are greyish-blue, extending most of the way down the tail. The [[rectrice]]s and tail tip are white. It has several [[bird vocalization|calls]], the most common being described as "cha-cha-cha-cha".

The white-tailed jay was first described by the French ornithologist {{ill|Louis Ernest Gustave de Sparre|de}} in 1835 and was given the [[binomial nomenclature|scientific name]] ''Pica mystacalis''. It was later placed in the genus ''Cyanocorax''. It is visually very similar to the [[tufted jay]], which is found in Mexico over {{cvt|4800|km|mi}} away, and the two species were incorrectly thought to be close relatives. The white-tailed jay's relationship to others in the genus ''Cyanocorax'' is still unclear.

The white-tailed jay lives in semi-humid, semi-open woodlands, preferring to remain near thick vegetation close to rivers and streams. It eats mostly insects and seeds, but has also been known to [[egg predation|steal eggs]] from the nests of other birds. It [[foraging|forages]] in [[flock (birds)|flocks]] and can be found feeding on the ground more often than other members of the genus ''Cyanocorax''. While little is known of its [[Bird#Breeding|breeding]] and [[nest|nesting]] habits, it is known to build nests through February and March and may nest close to villages. The white-tailed jay is considered a species of [[least concern]] by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]], although its population has seen notable decreases in some regions. The largest threat to its survival is [[habitat destruction]].

==Taxonomy and systematics==
[[File:Cyanocorax mystacalis.jpg|thumb|left|A drawing of the white-tailed jay done by de Sparre|alt=See caption]]

The white-tailed jay, also known as the moustached jay,{{sfnp|Goodwin|Gillmor|1976|p=300}} was first described in 1835 by the French ornithologist {{ill|Louis Ernest Gustave de Sparre|de}}, who placed it in the genus ''[[Pica (bird)|Pica]]'' with the [[Binomial nomenclature|scientific name]] ''Pica mystacalis''.{{sfnp|de Sparre|1832–1873|loc=Plate 34}} It is now placed in the genus ''[[Cyanocorax]]'', which was introduced by the German zoologist [[Friedrich Boie]] in 1826.{{sfnp|Boie|1826|loc=Col 975}}{{sfnp|Gill|Donsker|Rasmussen|2021}} The white-tailed jay has no recognized [[subspecies]].{{sfnp|Gill|Donsker|Rasmussen|2021}}

The white-tailed jay is visually similar to the [[tufted jay]] found in Mexico. The tufted jay lives within a restricted region of the [[Sierra Madre Occidental]], over {{cvt|4800|km|mi}} from the range of the white-tailed jay.{{sfnp|Moore|1935|p=275}} While many believed this was likely indicative of a [[common ancestor]] between the species, others proposed that the two might be the same species, and that the tufted jay had been brought to Mexico by [[pre-Columbian era|pre-Columbian trade]].{{sfnp|Haemig|1979|p=81}} In 2010, a [[mitochondrial DNA]] study of the genus ''Cyanocorax'' proved that the white-tailed jay was a distinct species from the tufted jay, and although they descend from a common ancestor, they are not particularly closely related. This study also demonstrated that the white-tailed jay was [[Monophyly|monophyletic]], although its exact position in relation to others in the genus was ambiguous.{{sfnp|Bonaccorso|Peterson|Navarro-Sigüenza|Fleischer|2010|pp=904}}

